assemblage.p:
The slope of a line is defined by the ratio
	\blert{\dfrac{\text{change in } y\text{-coordinate}}{\text{change in } x\text{-coordinate}}}
as we move from one point to another on the line. In symbols,
	\blert{m=\dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}}

A linear equation written in the form
		\blert{y=mx+b}
is said to be in slope-intercept form. The coefficient m is the slope of the graph, andb is the y-intercept.

li.p:
Two lines are parallel if their slopes are equal, that is, if
		\blert{m_1 = m_2}		
	or if both lines are vertical.

Two lines are perpendicular if the product of their slopes is -1, that is, if 
		\blert{m_1 m_2 = -1}
	or if one of the lines is horizontal and one is vertical.

